ital -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Missionary Interests, David Golding and Christopher Cannon Jones bring together works about Protestant and Mormon missionaries in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, charting new directions for the historical study of these zealous evangelists for their faith. Despite their sectarian differences, both groups of missionaries shared notions of dividing the world categorically along the lines of race, status, and relative exoticism, and both employed humanitarian outreach with designs to proselytize.American missionaries occupied liminal spaces: between proselytizer and proselytized, feminine and masculine, colonizer and colonized. Taken together, the chapters in Missionary Interests dismantle easy characterizations of missions and conversion and offer an overlooked juxtaposition between Mormon and Protestant missionary efforts in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLatter Day Saint missionariesxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aLatter Day Saint missionariesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLatter Day Saint missionariesxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aLatter Day Saint missionariesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLatter Day SaintsxMissionsxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aLatter Day SaintsxMissionsxHistoryy19th century. 0aLatter Day SaintsxMissionsxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aLatter Day SaintsxMissionsxHistoryy20th century. 0aMissionariesxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aMissionariesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionariesxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aMissionariesxHistoryy20th century. 0aProtestantsxMissionsxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aProtestantsxMissionsxHistoryy19th century. 0